This repo is a Rails 8 Bootstrap starter for WBEZ-style prototyping.

Follow these rules when generating or editing code:

## Core constraints
- Use Rails-native patterns: ERB partials, helpers, Turbo, Stimulus.
- Prefer Bootstrap layout and components over custom utility systems.
- Do not introduce Tailwind, daisyUI, React, Vue, or custom frontend architecture unless explicitly requested.
- Keep controllers thin and prefer display composition in partials/helpers.
- Do not modify the application's root route to point at demo pages (v2 template never does this; v1->v2 upgrade scripts remove any `root "demo#home"` if present).

## Canonical references
- `/demo` → component playground
- `/demo/home` → homepage-style reference
- `/demo/article` → article-page reference
- `/demo/cookbook` → editorial patterns reference
- `/demo/icons` → icon inventory
- `/demo/logos` → logo inventory

## Required conventions
- Reuse shared partials in `app/views/shared/ui` before writing new markup.
- If a new pattern is likely reusable, extract it as a partial.
- Use `.prose-wbez` for long-form editorial body content.
- Use serif treatment for editorial headlines and pull quotes.
- Use sans-serif treatment for UI, navigation, forms, metadata, and labels.

## Icons and logos
- Ferris icons are local SVGs in `app/assets/images/icons`.
- Always use `ferris_icon` or `inline_svg` for Ferris icons.
- Never use `image_tag` for Ferris icons.
- Use local logo assets from `app/assets/images/logos`.
- Do not hotlink CDN assets in views when a local asset exists.

## Good output characteristics
- Content-first
- restrained spacing
- readable hierarchy
- simple Bootstrap grid/layout
- WBEZ-like editorial tone
- reusable partial-based implementation

## Avoid
- one-off inline styles unless truly necessary
- novelty UI treatments
- arbitrary colors or spacing scales
- deeply nested custom HTML when an existing partial already matches
- JavaScript-heavy behavior when Turbo can handle it
